A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Criminal Law – Crimes Against Property – Right to Defend Property
3 FOR the purpose of establishing that an occupant of a dwelling or place of business is
4 justified in using any degree of physical force, under certain circumstances, and is
5 immune from criminal prosecution and civil liability for the use of the force;
6 providing certain exceptions to the provisions of this Act; and generally relating to
7 the defense of self–defense.
8 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
9 Article – Criminal Law
10 Section 3–209
11 Annotated Code of Maryland
12 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2024 Supplement)
13 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
14 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
15 Article – Criminal Law
16 3–209.
17 (a) Subject to subsection [(b)] (C) of this section, a person charged with a crime
18 under § 3–202, § 3–203, § 3–204, or § 3–205 of this subtitle may assert any judicially
19 recognized defense.
20 (B) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (4) OF THIS SUBSECTION, AN OCCUPANT
21 OF A DWELLING OR PLACE OF BUSINESS IS JUSTIFIED IN USING ANY DEGREE OF
22 PHYSICAL FORCE, INCLUDING DEADLY PHYSICAL FORCE, AGAINST ANOTHER
23 PERSON WHEN:
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
